title: Surveillance Vote in Senate Is Tangled in G.O.P. Debate
description: Unlike past partisan fights, the struggle over Patriot Act provisions on phone records, which is set to resume on Sunday, is an ideological battle pitting Republicans against one another.

title: In Carving Niche, Martin O’Malley Pushes Image of Vitality
description: At 52, former Gov. Martin O’Malley of Maryland aims to contrast himself with the Democratic candidates Hillary Rodham Clinton and Bernie Sanders.

title: Mohamed Soltan, U.S. Citizen Imprisoned in Egypt, Is Released
description: Mr. Soltan, who was arrested during the protests over the ouster of President Mohamed Morsi, gained attention through letters smuggled out of prison.

title: A Choice for Recovering Addicts: Relapse or Homelessness
description: Virtually unnoticed and effectively unregulated, a system of housing known as “three-quarter” homes profits off the poor and desperate in New York City.

title: Pakistan Launches Hunt for Bus Hijackers Who Killed 19
description: Pakistani security forces launched a major operation before dawn Saturday to hunt down gunmen who hijacked two buses and killed at least 19 passengers in the country's southwest, officials said.

title: Rangers Are Shut Out in Game 7 as Lightning Reach Finals
description: The Rangers’ season ended Friday when Tampa Bay took the deciding game of the Eastern Conference finals.

title: Jerry Dior, Designer of Major League Baseball’s Logo, Dies at 82
description: The logo was a routine assignment for Mr. Dior, completed in one afternoon, while he was working for Sandgren & Murtha, a New York City marketing concern.

title: Study Using Gay Canvassers Erred in Methods, Not Results, Author Says
description: Michael J. LaCour apologized for misrepresenting some aspects of the study about the effect gay canvassers can have in changing people’s minds about same-sex marriage.

title: Families Press for Changes in Policy on Hostages
description: A White House-ordered review is expected to produce recommendations such as a new interdepartmental “fusion cell” for recovering American captives, but not a shift in the government’s stance against ransom payments.

title: Obama Warns the Senate to Pass Surveillance Law
description: The president said the Senate was playing with fire if it failed to approve the USA Freedom Act this weekend.

title: Chinese Security Laws Elevate the Party and Stifle Dissent. Mao Would Approve.
description: The new law, released in draft form this month, says security must be maintained “to realize the great rejuvenation of the Chinese nation.”

title: Hastert Case Is Said to Be Linked to Decades-Old Sexual Abuse
description: Two people briefed on an F.B.I. investigation of J. Dennis Hastert, the former House speaker, said the payments were hush money to conceal misconduct during his years as a teacher.

title: Edward P. Gilligan, American Express Executive, Dies at 55
description: Mr. Gilligan was largely seen as the likely successor to Kenneth Chenault, the chief executive.

title: Ross Ulbricht, Creator of Silk Road Website, Is Sentenced to Life in Prison
description: Mr. Ulbricht was sentenced to life in prison for his role as what prosecutors described as “the kingpin of a worldwide digital drug-trafficking enterprise.”

title: Washington Memo: Once-Calming Leader and a Stunning Turn
description: J. Dennis Hastert was “the coach,” a colleague said. “He was a solid guy. He never raised his voice.”

title: Nikki Finke, Feared Hollywood Reporter, Turns to Fiction
description: Barred by a settlement from practicing journalism about the entertainment industry online, Ms. Finke is writing fiction for her new website, Hollywood Dementia.

title: First Draft: Bernie Sanders Recants 1972 Article on Women’s Fantasies of Rape
description: An article that Mr. Sanders wrote more than 40 years ago has resurfaced and he said it demonstrated how political campaigns can be like soap operas at times.

title: Sepp Blatter Withstands Scandal and Criticism to Secure a Fifth Term
description: Mr. Blatter emerged from a week marked by the arrest of several top soccer officials to win re-election as FIFA’s president.

title: U.S. Removes Cuba From State-Sponsored Terrorism List
description: The decision to remove Cuba from a list of state sponsors of terrorism is a crucial step in normalizing ties between Washington and Havana.

title: New York Nail Salons Now Required to Post Workers’ Bill of Rights
description: The placards are the latest effort by city and state leaders to curb the widespread exploitation of workers in the sprawling nail salon industry.
